  "prompt": "What is the difference between engine oils 0w-30, 5w-30, 10w-30?",
  "response": "The main difference between these engine oils lies in their viscosity grades, which indicate their performance at different temperatures:\n\n0W-30:\n- Thinnest and flows best at low temperatures\n- Provides quickest engine lubrication during cold starts\n- Best for extremely cold climates\n- Lower friction and improved fuel efficiency\n- Suitable for modern, high-performance engines\n\n5W-30:\n- Slightly thicker at low temperatures compared to 0W-30\n- Good cold-start performance\n- Versatile and widely used in many modern vehicles\n- Balanced performance in various temperature ranges\n- Recommended for many passenger cars and light trucks\n\n10W-30:\n- Thicker at low temperatures compared to 0W-30 and 5W-30\n- Less effective in very cold climates\n- Better for older engines or higher mileage vehicles\n- Provides good protection at higher temperatures\n- More suitable for warmer climates or older engine designs\n\nThe first number (0W, 5W, 10W) indicates the oil's viscosity at low temperatures, while the second number (30) represents the oil's viscosity at high temperatures. Lower first numbers mean better cold-start performance, and the second number indicates the oil's stability at operating temperatures.\n\nAlways consult your vehicle's manual for the recommended oil type.",
